title.en: Dublin Core Metadata Element Set, Version 1.1

title.value: Dublin Core Metadata Element Set, Version 1.1

comment.en: A location, period of time, or jurisdiction.
A process that is used to engender knowledge, attitudes, and skills.
A statement of any changes in ownership and custody of a resource since its creation that are significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation.
A media type or extent.
A physical material or carrier.

description.en: Examples include paper, canvas, or DVD.

comment.en: A legal document giving official permission to do something with a Resource.
An interval of time that is named or defined by its start and end dates.

comment.undefined: An image.

comment.en: A book, article, or other documentary resource.

comment.undefined: An online chat account.
A foaf:LabelProperty is any RDF property with texual values that serve as labels.
An online e-commerce account.

comment.en: A dimension or extent, or a time taken to play or execute.

description.en: Examples include a number of pages, a specification of length, width, and breadth, or a period in hours, minutes, and seconds.

comment.undefined: A document.
A project (a collective endeavour of some kind).

comment.en: A digital resource format.

description.en: Examples include the formats defined by the list of Internet Media Types.

comment.undefined: An online account.

definition.value: An idea or notion; a unit of thought.

comment.en: A statement about the intellectual property rights (IPR) held in or over a Resource, a legal document giving official permission to do something with a resource, or a statement about access rights.
A material thing.

definition.value: An enumerated set of resources.

comment.en: The extent or range of judicial, law enforcement, or other authority.
A system of signs, symbols, sounds, gestures, or rules used in communication.

description.en: Examples include written, spoken, sign, and computer languages.

comment.undefined: A class of Agents.

definition.value: An ordered collection of concepts, where both the grouping and the ordering are meaningful.

scopeNote.value: Ordered collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed in a specific order, and optionally under a 'node label'.

comment.en: A method by which resources are added to a collection.

comment.undefined: An agent (eg. person, group, software or physical artifact).

comment.en: A resource that acts or has the power to act.

description.en: Examples of Agent include person, organization, and software agent.

comment.en: A group of agents.

description.en: Examples of Agent Class include groups seen as classes, such as students, women, charities, lecturers.

comment.undefined: An organization.

comment.en: A spatial region or named place.

comment.undefined: An online gaming account.

comment.en: A basis for comparison; a reference point against which other things can be evaluated.

comment.undefined: A personal profile RDF document.

definition.value: A meaningful collection of concepts.

scopeNote.value: Labelled collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed under a 'node label' in the hierarchy.

comment.en: A rate at which something recurs.

definition.value: A set of concepts, optionally including statements about semantic relationships between those concepts.

scopeNote.value: A concept scheme may be defined to include concepts from different sources.

example.value: Thesauri, classification schemes, subject heading lists, taxonomies, 'folksonomies', and other types of controlled vocabulary are all examples of concept schemes. Concept schemes are also embedded in glossaries and terminologies.

comment.en: A file format or physical medium.
A plan or course of action by an authority, intended to influence and determine decisions, actions, and other matters.

comment.undefined: A person.
A work info homepage of some person; a page about their work for some organization.

comment.en: A person or organization owning or managing rights over the resource.
A language of the resource.

description.en: Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as RFC 4646 [RFC4646].

comment.undefined: A Yahoo chat ID

definition.value: Relates a resource (for example a concept) to a concept scheme in which it is included.

scopeNote.value: A concept may be a member of more than one concept scheme.

comment.undefined: The given name of some person.
A depiction of some thing.

comment.en: The method by which items are added to a collection.

comment.undefined: Title (Mr, Mrs, Ms, Dr. etc)

comment.en: An alternative name for the resource.

description.en: The distinction between titles and alternative titles is application-specific.

comment.en: A name given to the resource.

comment.undefined: A tipjar document for this agent, describing means for payment and reward.

definition.value: skos:broadMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

comment.en: The size or duration of the resource.

comment.undefined: An AIM chat ID

comment.en: A related resource that is required by the described resource to support its function, delivery, or coherence.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

definition.value: A notation, also known as classification code, is a string of characters such as "T58.5" or "303.4833" used to uniquely identify a concept within the scope of a given concept scheme.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:notation is used with a typed literal in the object position of the triple.

comment.undefined: Something that was made by this agent.

comment.en: An entity responsible for making the resource available.

description.en: Examples of a Publisher include a person, an organization, or a service.

comment.en: The file format, physical medium, or dimensions of the resource.

description.en: Examples of dimensions include size and duration. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the list of Internet Media Types [MIME].

comment.undefined: A Myers Briggs (MBTI) personality classification.

comment.en: A related resource that is substantially the same as the described resource, but in another format.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.undefined: A link to the publications of this person.
A page about a topic of interest to this person.
An OpenID for an Agent.
A project this person has previously worked on.
A person known by this person (indicating some level of reciprocated interaction between the parties).

comment.en: A legal document giving official permission to do something with the resource.

comment.undefined: The primary topic of some page or document.
The gender of this Agent (typically but not necessarily 'male' or 'female').

comment.en: Information about who can access the resource or an indication of its security status.

description.en: Access Rights may include information regarding access or restrictions based on privacy, security, or other policies.

comment.en: The spatial or temporal topic of the resource, the spatial applicability of the resource, or the jurisdiction under which the resource is relevant.

description.en: Spatial topic and spatial applicability may be a named place or a location specified by its geographic coordinates. Temporal topic may be a named period, date, or date range. A jurisdiction may be a named administrative entity or a geographic place to which the resource applies. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the Thesaurus of Geographic Names [TGN]. Where appropriate, named places or time periods can be used in preference to numeric identifiers such as sets of coordinates or date ranges.

comment.en: Spatial characteristics of the resource.

definition.value: skos:broaderTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:broader.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:broaderTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

comment.en: These concept mapping relations mirror semantic relations, and the data model defined below is similar (with the exception of skos:exactMatch) to the data model defined for semantic relations. A distinct vocabulary is provided for concept mapping relations, to provide a convenient way to differentiate links within a concept scheme from links between concept schemes. However, this pattern of usage is not a formal requirement of the SKOS data model, and relies on informal definitions of best practice.

definition.value: Relates two concepts coming, by convention, from different schemes, and that have comparable meanings

comment.en: An entity that mediates access to the resource and for whom the resource is intended or useful.

description.en: In an educational context, a mediator might be a parent, teacher, teaching assistant, or care-giver.

comment.en: An entity primarily responsible for making the resource.

description.en: Examples of a Creator include a person, an organization, or a service.

comment.en: skos:related is disjoint with skos:broaderTransitive

definition.value: Relates a concept to a concept with which there is an associative semantic relationship.

comment.undefined: A page or document about this thing.

comment.en: Date of creation of the resource.
A related resource from which the described resource is derived.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

description.en: The described resource may be derived from the related resource in whole or in part. Recommended best practice is to identify the related resource by means of a string conforming to a formal identification system.

comment.undefined: A name for some thing.
An ICQ chat ID
The family name of some person.

comment.en: Date of formal issuance (e.g., publication) of the resource.
A related resource that is substantially the same as the pre-existing described resource, but in another format.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.en: A related resource that is supplanted, displaced, or superseded by the described resource.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.undefined: A Skype ID

comment.en: An unambiguous reference to the resource within a given context.

description.en: Recommended best practice is to identify the resource by means of a string conforming to a formal identification system.

comment.undefined: A topic of some page or document.
The first name of a person.

definition.value: Relates a concept to the concept scheme that it is a top level concept of.

comment.undefined: A .plan comment, in the tradition of finger and '.plan' files.

comment.en: Information about rights held in and over the resource.

description.en: Typically, rights information includes a statement about various property rights associated with the resource, including intellectual property rights.

definition.value: skos:narrowMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

comment.undefined: The underlying or 'focal' entity associated with some SKOS-described concept.
A textual geekcode for this person, see http://www.geekcode.com/geek.html
A string expressing what the user is happy for the general public (normally) to know about their current activity.

comment.en: A related resource in which the described resource is physically or logically included.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.undefined: Indicates a homepage of the service provide for this online account.
A homepage for some thing.
An MSN chat ID
A thing of interest to this person.
A current project this person works on.

comment.en: An established standard to which the described resource conforms.

comment.undefined: The birthday of this Agent, represented in mm-dd string form, eg. '12-31'.
Indicates a member of a Group

A  personal mailbox, ie. an Internet mailbox associated with exactly one owner, the first owner of this mailbox. This is a 'static inverse functional property', in that  there is (across time and change) at most one individual that ever has any particular value for foaf:mbox.
The surname of some person.

definition.value: skos:narrowerTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:narrower.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:narrowerTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

definition.value: Links a concept to a concept related by meaning.

scopeNote.value: This property should not be used directly, but as a super-property for all properties denoting a relationship of meaning between concepts.

comment.en: Date on which the resource was changed.
A point or period of time associated with an event in the lifecycle of the resource.

description.en: Date may be used to express temporal information at any level of granularity.  Recommended best practice is to use an encoding scheme, such as the W3CDTF profile of ISO 8601 [W3CDTF].

comment.en: The frequency with which items are added to a collection.

comment.undefined: The given name of some person.
A checksum for the DNA of some thing. Joke.
A document that this thing is the primary topic of.

comment.en: skos:exactMatch is disjoint with each of the properties skos:broadMatch and skos:relatedMatch.

definition.value: skos:exactMatch is used to link two concepts, indicating a high degree of confidence that the concepts can be used interchangeably across a wide range of information retrieval applications. skos:exactMatch is a transitive property, and is a sub-property of skos:closeMatch.

comment.undefined: Indicates an account held by this agent.

comment.en: A bibliographic reference for the resource.

description.en: Recommended practice is to include sufficient bibliographic detail to identify the resource as unambiguously as possible.

comment.en: A class of entity for whom the resource is intended or useful.

comment.undefined: An image that can be used to represent some thing (ie. those depictions which are particularly representative of something, eg. one's photo on a homepage).
A sha1sum hash, in hex.
The family name of some person.

comment.en: A process, used to engender knowledge, attitudes and skills, that the described resource is designed to support.

description.en: Instructional Method will typically include ways of presenting instructional materials or conducting instructional activities, patterns of learner-to-learner and learner-to-instructor interactions, and mechanisms by which group and individual levels of learning are measured.  Instructional methods include all aspects of the instruction and learning processes from planning and implementation through evaluation and feedback.

comment.en:
For any resource, every item in the list given as the value of the
      skos:memberList property is also a value of the skos:member property.

definition.value: Relates an ordered collection to the RDF list containing its members.

comment.undefined: A short informal nickname characterising an agent (includes login identifiers, IRC and other chat nicknames).

comment.en: A related resource of which the described resource is a version, edition, or adaptation.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

description.en: Changes in version imply substantive changes in content rather than differences in format.

comment.undefined: A theme.
A phone,  specified using fully qualified tel: URI scheme (refs: http://www.w3.org/Addressing/schemes.html#tel).

definition.value: skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. In order to avoid the possibility of "compound errors" when combining mappings across more than two concept schemes, skos:closeMatch is not declared to be a transitive property.

comment.undefined: An organization funding a project or person.
The age in years of some agent.

comment.en: A related resource that is referenced, cited, or otherwise pointed to by the described resource.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.en: Broader concepts are typically rendered as parents in a concept hierarchy (tree).

definition.value: Relates a concept to a concept that is more general in meaning.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

comment.undefined: Indicates an account held by this agent.
A derived thumbnail image.
A weblog of some thing (whether person, group, company etc.).

definition.value: A relationship between a resource and a vocabulary encoding scheme which indicates that the resource is a member of a set.

comment.en: A related resource that supplants, displaces, or supersedes the described resource.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.undefined: A workplace homepage of some person; the homepage of an organization they work for.

comment.en: Narrower concepts are typically rendered as children in a concept hierarchy (tree).

definition.value: Relates a concept to a concept that is more specific in meaning.

scopeNote.value: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

comment.en: Date (often a range) of validity of a resource.

comment.undefined: A location that something is based near, for some broadly human notion of near.

comment.en: Date of acceptance of the resource.

description.en: Examples of resources to which a Date Accepted may be relevant are a thesis (accepted by a university department) or an article (accepted by a journal).

definition.value: Relates, by convention, a concept scheme to a concept which is topmost in the broader/narrower concept hierarchies for that scheme, providing an entry point to these hierarchies.

comment.en: The policy governing the addition of items to a collection.
An entity responsible for making contributions to the resource.

description.en: Examples of a Contributor include a person, an organization, or a service.

comment.en: Temporal characteristics of the resource.

definition.value: skos:relatedMatch is used to state an associative mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.
Relates a collection to one of its members.

label.undefined: sha1sum of a personal mailbox URI name

comment.undefined: The sha1sum of the URI of an Internet mailbox associated with exactly one owner, the  first owner of the mailbox.

comment.en: Date (often a range) that the resource became or will become available.
A related resource that references, cites, or otherwise points to the described resource.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.en: A class of entity, defined in terms of progression through an educational or training context, for which the described resource is intended.
Date of submission of the resource.

description.en: Examples of resources to which a Date Submitted may be relevant are a thesis (submitted to a university department) or an article (submitted to a journal).

comment.undefined: A thing depicted in this representation.
A homepage of a school attended by the person.
The last name of a person.

comment.en: A statement of any changes in ownership and custody of the resource since its creation that are significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation.

description.en: The statement may include a description of any changes successive custodians made to the resource.

comment.undefined: A logo representing some thing.
Indicates the name (identifier) associated with this online account.
A jabber ID for something.

comment.en: A related resource that is a version, edition, or adaptation of the described resource.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.en: Date of copyright.
A related resource that is included either physically or logically in the described resource.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.en: The material or physical carrier of the resource.
A related resource that requires the described resource to support its function, delivery, or coherence.

note.value: This term is intended to be used with non-literal values as defined in the DCMI Abstract Model (http://dublincore.org/documents/abstract-model/).  As of December 2007, the DCMI Usage Board is seeking a way to express this intention with a formal range declaration.

comment.undefined: An agent that  made this thing.

comment.en: The nature or genre of the resource.

description.en: Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the DCMI Type Vocabulary [DCMITYPE]. To describe the file format, physical medium, or dimensions of the resource, use the Format element.
